  "Diatom blooms": "",
  "Brown algae blooms": "",
  "Green algae blooms": "",
  "Harmful algal blooms (HABs), often caused by cyanobacteria (blue-green algae), can produce potent toxins called cyanotoxins that are dangerous to humans, pets, livestock, and wildlife, sometimes contaminating drinking water supplies.": "",
  "What is the primary agricultural source of nitrogen that contributes to eutrophication?": "",
  "Synthetic fertilizer runoff and animal manure": "",
  "Crop harvesting": "",
  "Irrigation water": "",
  "Pesticide application": "",
  "Synthetic nitrogen fertilizers and animal manure are the primary agricultural sources of nitrogen pollution. Excess nitrogen not absorbed by crops is washed into waterways by rainfall and irrigation, fueling downstream eutrophication.": "",
  "How do algal blooms reduce light availability in water?": "",
  "They reflect all sunlight back into the atmosphere": "",
  "They release chemicals that darken the water permanently": "",
  "They absorb all water in the system": "",
  "Dense algal growth at the surface blocks sunlight from reaching submerged aquatic vegetation": "",
  "Thick algal blooms form dense mats on the water surface that block sunlight from penetrating deeper water. This shading kills submerged aquatic plants that need light for photosynthesis, further degrading the ecosystem.": "",
